WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.640
Hi, my name is Richard Vogg and I'm happy to be here and talk about how I became a data

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:14.200
composer.

00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:19.320
This ability of composing data or creating data from scratch has been increasingly helpful

00:00:19.320 --> 00:00:21.200
for me at my last job.

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:25.480
I was working for a data analytics company in Chile for the last years and the client

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:31.120
that we were supporting with analytics was one of the largest banks in the United States.

00:00:31.120 --> 00:00:36.840
Similar to a music composer who assembles musical notes and chords into melodies and

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:41.080
songs I started to play around with datasets.

00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:45.240
Using R it is very easy to get started, it is fun to get started as many of you might

00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:47.840
also have experienced.

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:52.680
For example it is very easy to create a thousand random normally distributed variables and

00:00:52.680 --> 00:00:58.560
we can also easily create variables from other distributions like the exponential distribution

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:03.880
or we can create categorical variables by using the sample function.

00:01:03.880 --> 00:01:08.739
We can combine all those variables in a data frame and then we have our first in this case

00:01:08.739 --> 00:01:12.199
nonsense dataset ready.

00:01:12.199 --> 00:01:16.720
And then we can go and take a look at the data and we can check if what we composed

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:21.160
is actually what we wanted to compose, if it makes sense.

00:01:21.160 --> 00:01:26.239
So I started to create small melodies, small data melodies in the beginning because it

00:01:26.239 --> 00:01:29.559
was fun and later because it was useful.

00:01:29.559 --> 00:01:34.959
I used this skill in the business world to improve the communication with non-technical

00:01:34.959 --> 00:01:35.959
business partners.

00:01:35.959 --> 00:01:42.279
So I created small and easy datasets and visualizations about topics that the business partners felt

00:01:42.279 --> 00:01:47.919
comfortable with and used them to explain concepts, explain methods and in general to

00:01:47.919 --> 00:01:52.879
create a common ground for discussion and for questions.

00:01:52.879 --> 00:01:57.120
When you compose a song for your band it is not enough to have a beautiful melody for

00:01:57.120 --> 00:02:01.980
each one of the instruments but you also want them to sound good together.

00:02:01.980 --> 00:02:06.680
So in DataWords we do not only want independent variables but we also want them to make some

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:12.559
sort of sense together and I trained that skill and used it a lot because we were working

00:02:12.559 --> 00:02:18.679
with sensitive data so you could not just send data to someone else with a question

00:02:18.679 --> 00:02:23.160
because not everyone had the same level of access to the data.

00:02:23.160 --> 00:02:29.160
And instead I quickly assembled a suitable dataset for each occasion and was able to

00:02:29.160 --> 00:02:35.360
ask questions but also to give advice without having to see the real data or having to touch

00:02:35.360 --> 00:02:37.720
the real data.

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:42.160
Another application emerged when we had more and more agile projects so we had this aim

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:47.960
of having a working deliverable in each iteration and this was sometimes hard to reach because

00:02:47.960 --> 00:02:52.759
we had to wait a lot of time for the data so we had to talk to the data owner, sometimes

00:02:52.759 --> 00:02:57.440
request accesses, we had to bring the data into the right format.

00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:02.759
And by using a composed dataset that looked like the expected final dataset we could already

00:03:02.759 --> 00:03:09.399
start to work on the output, on the report and while we were still waiting for the real

00:03:09.399 --> 00:03:14.759
data and in the end we simply replaced that composed dataset with the real dataset and

00:03:14.759 --> 00:03:18.440
improved the whole process a lot.

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:22.240
When you want to write a symphony you're not just aligning a few instruments but you have

00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:28.440
actually blocks or groups of instruments that have to sound good together and in DataWords

00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:35.119
that could be a database where you have several tables that are all connected with each other.

00:03:35.119 --> 00:03:39.960
And it is not easy to create a complete database from scratch but we still did it to improve

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:45.679
our internal courses so we wanted to make those courses closer to what we actually work

00:03:45.679 --> 00:03:52.960
with and we created a client table, transaction table, account tables and combined all of

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:57.479
them and made this whole database available to everyone in the company, to the internal

00:03:57.479 --> 00:04:03.520
courses and also for small prototypes and projects.

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:06.880
All this was about why data composition is important.

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:11.679
Now how to compose with R, there are of course the distributions I already showed in the

00:04:11.679 --> 00:04:16.839
beginning how easy it is to work with the distributions and there are also a lot of

00:04:16.839 --> 00:04:22.079
functions that can help you to correlate your simulated data to create those connections

00:04:22.079 --> 00:04:26.760
between the variables, there are functions that help you to create the relations between

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:32.200
tables and of course there are a lot of packages out there that just wait to be explored that

00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:37.239
can support you on your data composition process.

00:04:37.239 --> 00:04:42.519
And as I just have a few seconds left I wrote a blog post for each one of those four points,

00:04:42.519 --> 00:04:49.480
you can, I invite you to visit my blog and there are a lot more details about those topics

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:54.160
and I hope they might be helpful for you to become a data composer too.

00:04:54.160 --> 00:04:55.640
Thank you very much for your attention.

